    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-11-07T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-11-07T10:00:00-05:00" n="366"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d366">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">815.00/2735: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Honduras</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morales</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tegucigalpa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-11-07T09:00:00-06:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 7, 1923—9 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>91. The political situation in Honduras is more complicated today than prior to
                    the elections. Bonilla is making overtures to Arias for a fusion of the two
                    factions to defeat Carias in Congress. Arias is also trying to come to some
                    arrangement with Carias. The Government <pb facs="0568" n="444" xml:id="pg_444"
                    /> favors a union between Arias and Bonilla for the interest of the Liberal
                    Party with the latter as President. In this event a revolution is inevitable as
                    Carias is determined to fight for his right to the office. In my opinion the
                    only solution to the controversy is a fusion between Carias and Arias or between
                    Carias and Bonilla. My assistance in bringing about an agreement has been
                    solicited by Arias and Bonilla. I feel certain that Carias would be willing to
                    enter into an arrangement with one or the other but only on the basis that he be
                    the President. The Department’s advice in this matter is requested.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Morales</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
